/////////function pointer chaining example///////////////
 #include <stdio.h>
        void first()
        {
            printf("first");
        }
        void second()
        {
            first();
        }
        void third()
        {
            second();
        }
            
        void main()
        {
            void (*ptr)();
            ptr = third;
            ptr();
        }

Output: first
/////////////////////

🧠 1️⃣ What is ptr?
void (*ptr)();

👉 ptr is a pointer to a function
👉 The function takes no arguments and returns void

🧠 2️⃣ Assignment
ptr = third;
This means:
ptr → address of function third

🧠 3️⃣ Function call using pointer
ptr();

Equivalent to:

third();
🔁 4️⃣ Function Call Flow

Let’s trace execution:

main()
  ↓
ptr() → third()
  ↓
third() calls second()
  ↓
second() calls first()
  ↓
first() prints "first"
🖨 5️⃣ Output
first
🧠 6️⃣ Call Stack View
main
 └── third
      └── second
           └── first

Only first() prints output.

🧠 7️⃣ Important Concepts
✔ Function pointer syntax
void (*ptr)();
✔ Assign function to pointer
ptr = third;
✔ Call function using pointer
ptr();   // same as third()
🧠 8️⃣ Equivalent Normal Code
int main()
{
    third();   // directly calling
}

Same output:

first
🎓 Interview One-Line Answer

The function pointer ptr points to third(), which calls second(), which calls first(), so the final output is "first".

🔥 Bonus (Interview Twist)

If we change:

void (*ptr)() = first;
ptr();

Output would be:

first

But no chaining happens.
